                <TextBlock Text="Section 1: Introduction" FontSize="20" FontWeight="Bold" Margin="10" Name="Introduction" />
                <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Margin="10">
                   Life Cycle Costing (LCC) considers all the costs that will be incurred during the lifetime of a product, work or service, and can be calculated as function of a product’s service life. The ForestValue2 project, WoodLCC, seeks to enable robust and precise LCC of wooden components and buildings, compatible with LCC calculation standards EN 16627 (2015) and EN 15643-4 (2021), based on input from detailed service life performance models. The actual service life of a given component or building is the result of a complex set of factors including its design, material properties, location of exposure, engineering, level of maintenance, workmanship, and intensity of use. LCC is one of the basic indicators for sustainability assessment and cost effectiveness applicable in construction. By attaining data on wood material costs, labour and installation costs, inflation and escalation costs, wood material degradation rate, and user preferences for aesthetic change, a holistic LCC estimate for wooden components will be realised. Starting from the design phase through to the end-of-life phase, the addition of such an LCC calculation tool to an already established building information modelling (BIM) software would enable optimization of the entire life performance of timber buildings and their constituent components. WoodLCC has reached numerous technical milestones related to accurate predictions of wood service life, which now include simulations of driving rain and moisture exposure, solar and temperature exposure, and aesthetic change or greying. These simulations can now be implemented on a building design with the help of a working prototype plug-in, compatible with industry-norm architectural design software. Project WoodLCC ran from April 2022 until the end of April 2025.
                </TextBlock>
                
